      <p>For this guide, we compared each model against the same buyer reality: people want better espresso at home without crossing the $200 line. That means recommendation quality depends on practical trade-offs, not spec-sheet hype. We scored each machine across shot consistency potential, milk-drink workflow, learning curve, cleanup friction, and long-term ownership value.</p>
      <p>Shot consistency potential focuses on how repeatable a machine feels when you use an espresso-capable grind and basic puck prep. Some models look similar in marketing photos but behave very differently once you brew back-to-back drinks. We favored options that feel forgiving enough for beginners while still rewarding better grind control over time.</p>
      <p>Milk workflow matters because many shoppers in this tier are buying for cappuccinos and lattes, not straight shots only. We separated manual and automatic milk systems so readers can choose based on routine: if you enjoy learning texture control, manual can be stronger; if you need speed at 7 AM, automatic systems can be the right call.</p>
      <p>Finally, we weighted daily friction. A machine that makes okay coffee but fits your routine beats a technically better machine that you avoid using. Cleanup design, refill access, and part availability all influence whether a budget buy actually turns into daily value.</p>
