      <p>The easiest mistake in this budget is chasing feature lists without matching your routine. Start with your weekday reality: do you want better espresso craft, faster milk drinks, or minimal cleanup? The answer should decide your machine category before you compare model names.</p>

      <h3>Step 1: pick your workflow type first</h3>
      <p>If you enjoy learning extraction and milk technique, choose a semi-automatic or manual setup. If your main goal is quick, repeatable drinks, convenience-focused systems often deliver better real-world value even if they have a lower espresso ceiling.</p>

      <h3>Step 2: budget for grinder and scale, not just the machine</h3>
      <p>In this tier, grind consistency has more impact than small machine differences. If your grinder is inconsistent, even a good machine produces uneven cups. For practical setup planning, pair this guide with our <a href="/posts/best-burr-grinder-for-espresso.html">best burr grinder for espresso</a> and <a href="/posts/burr-grinder-settings-for-espresso.html">espresso grind settings guide</a>.</p>

      <h3>Step 3: check maintenance tolerance before you buy</h3>
      <p>Every machine here needs routine cleaning to stay consistent. Some have easier drip-tray access and simpler milk cleanup than others. If you know you dislike maintenance, choose the model with the least friction because that is what keeps quality stable over months.</p>
